## Research Brief: Stripe Integration for Node.js/Fastify

**Audience:** Architect + Executor | **Codebase:** Fastify v4.28.1, TypeScript ESM, Node ≥ 18, Zod, Vitest

---

## 1. Recommended Node.js Stripe SDK Setup

**Install (server-side only):**

```bash
npm install stripe
```

**Current SDK version:** v21.0.1 | **Current API version:** `2026-04-22.dahlia`

**Canonical docs:** [stripe-node README](https://github.com/stripe/stripe-node) · [Dev environment setup](https://docs.stripe.com/get-started/development-environment?lang=node)

### Client Instantiation — Use Lazy Initialization

The SDK throws at import time if `STRIPE_SECRET_KEY` is missing. Since this codebase loads all routes at startup (see `buildApp` in `src/app.ts`), a top-level `new Stripe(...)` will crash in CI/test if the key is absent. Use a lazy singleton:

```typescript
// src/payments/stripe-client.ts
import Stripe from 'stripe';

let _client: Stripe | undefined;

export function getStripeClient(): Stripe {
  if (!_client) {
    const key = process.env.STRIPE_SECRET_KEY;
    if (!key) throw new Error('STRIPE_SECRET_KEY is not set');
    _client = new Stripe(key, {
      apiVersion: '2026-04-22.dahlia',
      maxNetworkRetries: 2,   // safe with idempotency keys
      timeout: 10_000,
    });
  }
  return _client;
}
```

**Config options that matter:**

| Option | Recommended | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `apiVersion` | `'2026-04-22.dahlia'` | Pin explicitly; don't rely on account default |
| `maxNetworkRetries` | `2` | SDK auto-retries with generated idempotency keys; safe for GET + idempotent POSTs |
| `timeout` | `10_000` | Default 80 s is too long for a web request; fail fast |

