---

### Bugs Fixed

#### [FIXED] `src/config/pino-config.ts` — dead-code branch, body always stripped

**Severity: High.** The `serializeRequest` function never included `body` in `serialized` for any route. Both the early-return path and the fall-through path returned the identical object (no `body` key). The branch `if (!isSensitivePath)` was dead code:

```46:67:src/config/pino-config.ts
function serializeRequest(request: {
  method?: string;
  url?: string;
  hostname?: string;
  ip?: string;
  socket?: { remotePort?: number };
  body?: unknown;
}): Record<string, unknown> {
  const serialized: Record<string, unknown> = {
    method: request.method,
    url: request.url,
    hostname: request.hostname,
    remoteAddress: request.ip,
    remotePort: request.socket?.remotePort,
  };

  if (isSensitivePath(request.url)) {
    return serialized;
  }

  if (request.body !== undefined) {
    serialized.body = request.body;
  }

  return serialized;
}
```

Body is now included for non-sensitive routes and excluded for `/payments/*` and `/webhooks/*`. The pino-config test was expanded to assert body IS present for non-sensitive paths, which also guards against regression.

> Note for executor: `REDACT_PATHS` still contains `req.body` globally. Pino will redact this field on any route where it appears in the serialized log object. That's belt-and-suspenders fine, but be aware body never reaches the redactor on sensitive paths (the serializer strips it first). The redact entries for `req.body.card_number`, `req.body.cvc`, etc. only fire if a non-sensitive route logs a request with those fields — that remains correct and useful.

